OL,3,C'The village died... never recovered':
OL,4,CWhy the miners' strike still matters
OL,6,FThere are former miners who believe
OL,7,Fthat outcome may have been different
OL,8,Fif a national ballot had been held
OL,9,Finstead of being left in the hands of
OL,10,Fdifferent NUM regions and individual
OL,11,Fpits. Twenty miles or so down the M1
OL,12,Fin North Anston, near , I meet Graham
OL,13,FYeates, who was an underground fitter
OL,14,Fat Cortonwood - the first pit to walk
OL,15,Fout. In 1984 he led teams of pickets
OL,16,Facross the region. Even so, he says he
OL,17,Funderstood why some men chose to cross
OL,18,Fthose picket lines."
